<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06150046 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06150046 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Rafsanjani  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; FOREIGN; RELATION; IRAN; KIDNAPPING; VICTIM  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Bush administration said Tuesday that it would not move to improverelations with Iran until Tehran used its influence to obtain the release ofsix U.S. hostages held by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon.;    Senioradministration officials greeted commitments by senior Iranian leaders to seekcloser ties with both their Arab neighbors and the West with varying degreesof skepticism and little enthusiasm.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IMPROVED RELATIONS WITH TEHRAN HINGE ON RELEASEOF HOSTAGES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     They said it was premature to consider modifying U.S. policy toward Iran.Washington has made any improvement in relations contingent on the hostages'release.;    'A new order';  Some U.S. officials, including State Departmentspokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, gave no indication that the United States waseager for a better relationship with Tehran, repeating the longstandingcondition that Iran end its support for international terrorism.;    Othersenior officials offered a more subtle interpretation that took into account aseries of actions in Tehran, saying remarks by President Hashemi Rafsanjaniand other officials about &quot;a new order&quot; based more on economic developmentthan political goals were encouraging.;    When asked whether the UnitedStates believed that Iran held the key to the hostages' release, Tutwilerreplied, &quot;All those who have influence should bring influence to bear, andobviously, it goes without question Iran has influence.&quot;;    Open terrorismquestion;  Reflecting the more favorable view in the administration, onesenior official said: &quot;There is a general, although not universal, pattern ofrestraint in Iranian foreign policy, and one sees an effort by Iran to reduceits self-imposed isolation. We are open to a better relationship but we arenot going to run after it. And the question of the hostages and terrorism isstill out there.&quot;;    Independent scholars on Iran said they had hoped theadministration would respond to the policy articulated by Iranian officials atthe start of an international oil conference in Isfahan on Monday with aconciliatory move.;    &quot;One could have seized on this opportunity to make somesmall gesture toward the Iranians,&quot; said Patrick Clawson, an economist andexpert on both Iran and Iraq at the Philadelphia-based Foreign Policy ResearchInstitute.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910529  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  348  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 29, 199100150046,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>